In measure theory, the integral of a scalar multiple is the scalar multiple of the integral: $\int r \cdot f \, d\mu = r \cdot \int f \, d\mu$. Therefore, if $\int f \, d\mu$ exists, then $\int r \cdot f \, d\mu$ exists and equals $r \cdot \int f \, d\mu$. Conversely, if $\int r \cdot f \, d\mu$ exists, then $\int f \, d\mu$ exists and equals $\frac{1}{r} \cdot \int r \cdot f \, d\mu$ when $r \neq 0$.

